                  <additions>
                    <list>
                      <item xml:id="a01">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#141v"/> (col. 1): Concluding Prayer of Gate of Light [Anqäsä Bərhan ],
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">
                      ጸሎታ፡ ለማርያም፡ ወስእለታ፡ ለሕዝበ፡ ክርስቲያን፡ ያድኅነነ፡ ኢመዓተ፡ ወልዳ። ጸሎታ፡ ለማርያም፡ ወስእለታ፡ ለገብረ፡ ሕይወት፡ ያድኅኖ፡ እመዓተ፡ ወልዳ ። ጸሎታ፡ ለማርያም፡ ወስእለታ፡ ለወለተ፡ አረጋዊ፡ ያድኅና፡ እመዓተ፡ ወልዳ።
                      </foreign>
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a02">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#141v #142r #142"/>: Table Prayer, “We beseech you,” Sä’alnakä, <foreign xml:lang="gez">ሰአልናከ፡</foreign>, (MD59 634ff). (incomplete at the end)
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">...ሰአልናከ፡ መሐሪ፡ ናስተበቊዓከ፡ ዘኢትፈልእ(ጥ)፡ ወኢትከልፅ፡ ወኢትሌሊ፡ የማንከ፡ ነቅዓ፡ ሕይወት፡...</foreign>
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a03">
                      <desc type="ScribalNoteCommissioning">
                      <locus target="#141v"/>, col.1: Copied for Gäbrä Ḥəywät and Wälättä Arägawi
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e01">
                      <desc>
                        This codex has all of the marks of having been produced in the earlytwentieth
                        century government scriptorium: finely tooled leather,
                        trimmed turn-ins, fabric pasted to front and back boards, distinctive
                        harägs, the head band and tail band are two-toned, with white and
                        red strips of leather, fine and regular parchment, etc
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e02">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#ir(ecto) #iv(erso) #iir(ecto) #iiv(erso) #iiir(ecto) #iiiv(erso) #ivr(ecto) #ivv(erso) #143r #143v #144r #144v"/> blank save for a few letters and pen trials
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e03">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#53v"/>: The text “half of it is here” is written the margin and enclosed in an ornate box to mark the midpoint of the psalms. The symbol is one line above the normal location
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e04">
                      <desc>
                      Psalm 118 contains the spiritual meanings of the Hebrew letters
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e05">
                      <desc>
                      Numbered quires: quires 2–7
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e06">
                      <desc>
                      words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#20r #113r"/>);
                      and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#3r #24v #70r #80v #84r"/>, etc.);
                      erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#114r"/>)
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e07">
                      <desc>
                        This scribe has avoided the problem of lines of text too long to fit on one line by adopting an aspect ratio that leaves ample room for the
                        width of most lines. On a few occasions, the line would have been too long and the scribe finishes the end of the line with words written
                        smaller so as to avoid leftover text (e.g., <locus target="#11v #14r #16v #17v"/>).
                        Occasionally a line is still too long and has to be completed above or below the end of the line. In these cases, the scribe places the
                        material above the line (e.g., <locus target="#6v #108r #115v"/>)
                      </desc>
                      </item>

                    </list>
